{
"knowledge": "In large‑scale language‑model pretraining with 2.14×10⁸ parameters trained on ≈10⁸ tokens, the learning rate and batch size influence both variance and bias of gradient estimates. Very low rates (<2×10⁻⁴) lead to extremely slow loss improvement, while very high rates (>6×10⁻³) can cause loss spikes and instability. Batch sizes ≤128 introduce high gradient noise, biasing valuation loss upward, whereas extreme large batches (≥4096) can mask sub‑optimal updates.",
"expected_structure": "The optimal validation loss is expected to occur near the moderate learning rate 3.906e‑3 and the batch size 256, a balance between good convergence and low gradient variance.",
"approach": "Execute experiments in non‑decreasing order of learning rate while holding batch size fixed at 256, to locate where the validation loss begins to rise and thus identify the optimal pair.",
"uncertainties": [
 "Whether the stated optimal loss will be lower at an even higher learning rate paired with a larger batch size (e.g., 6.905e‑3 lr & 256 bs).",
 "If gradient bias from small batch sizes outweighs any benefit of a higher learning rate beyond a point."
]
}

